subSection.paragraph:
Despite its effective use in breeding for over 100 years (
Dyck et al., 1966
), as well as its cloning (
Krattinger et al., 2009
) and the recent biochemical characterization of its encoded ABC transporter (
Rajagopalan et al., 2016
; 
Deppe et al., 2018
; 
Krattinger et al., 2019
), the mechanism by which 
Lr34res
elicits its durable quantitative rust resistance remains to be fully understood. 
A
clearer picture of its molecular mechanism of action will allow more rational implementation of its use in breeding programs, most notably when it comes to stacking sources of resistance to enable the development of more durable qualitative resistance as fungal pathogens continue to change and adapt.

With respect to increased accumulation of 
CFG
arising directly from functionalities of the encoded LR34res ABC transporter, the possibility of active transport of phenylpropanoid diglycerides, or related precursor/possible breakdown HCA metabolites such as ferulic and coumaric acids, remains to be tested. This is an attractive possibility considering the structural similarities between ABA (known LR34res allocrite; 
Krattinger et al., 2019
) and HCA, which include single modified six carbon rings with short acid carbon-chain tails. Alternatively, as proposed by others with respect to another APR-linked transporter (
Lr67res
; 
Moore et al., 2015
), accumulation of 
CFG
could be associated with inhibition of transport by LR34res, compared to LR34sus, such that more of the metabolites are retained within the plant cell, as a reserve for plant defense.

That the accumulation of CFG’ s could instead be indirectly arising from documented functionalities of LR34res, including either phospholipid leaflet translocation or ABA transport activities and their associated induced gene responses, cannot be ignored (
Deppe et al., 2018
; 
Krattinger et al., 2019
). ABA, which is produced by many fungal species (
Takino et al., 2018
) and has been linked to both susceptibility and resistance depending on the 
type
of pathogen (
Ton et al., 2009
), is generally thought to serve as a susceptibility factor (effector) in pathogenic plant-fungal interactions (for e.g. (
Ward et al., 1989
; 
Audenaert et al., 2002
; Asselbergh et al., 2007; 
Qi et al., 2015
; 
Gordon et al., 2016
; 
Buhrow et al., 2016
); with some exceptions (e.g. 
De Vleesschauwer et al., 2010
)). On this basis one might speculate that increased transport of ABA, and associated ABA responses in 
Lr34res
plants (
Hulbert et al., 2007
; 
Krattinger et al., 2019
), represents a constitutive ABA-like priming effect, upregulating classical plant defense responses even in the absence of a pathogen (as discussed in (
Hulbert et al., 2007
)). However, ABA-induced upregulation of phenylpropanoid biosynthetic gene expression has not been highlighted across any global transcriptomic ABA-priming study to date (
Goda, 2008
; 
Garg et al., 2012
; 
Kakei et al., 2015
; 
Dalal et al., 2018
). At the same time any association between modulation of LR34res phospholipid translocation (
Deppe et al., 2018
) and phenylpropanoid biosynthesis is not expected based on currently documented pathways. As an aside, a recent report does link increased accumulation of the anti-fungal metabolite ergosterol to modulation of lipid biosynthetic genes in soybean (
Ranjan et al., 2019
). None-the-less, a more targeted full analysis of the modulation of the phenylpropanoid pathway across ABA-primed and lipid leaflet modulated transcriptomic data sets could better inform this aspect in the future.
